The fish has been diagnosed with Tail Rot Disease, which is characterized by congestion and inflammation of the caudal fin and caudal peduncle. In severe cases, the caudal fin may rot away, and even the entire tail section can be affected. The disease is caused by bacteria such as Aeromonas sobria, Aeromonas caviae, and Aeromonas hydrophila. It is susceptible to infect grass carp, channel catfish, tilapia, snakehead fish, and dark-striped loach .
